  "dateModified": "2026-03-03",
  "datePublished": "2026-03-03",
  "description": "The friend/enemy distinction is Carl Schmitt\u0026rsquo;s foundational concept from The Concept of the Political (1932) [cite:@schmitt_ConceptPolitical_2007]. Schmitt argued that the defining criterion of the political is not right and wrong, not good and bad, not profitable and unprofitable, but friend and enemy. The political enemy is not a personal adversary, a competitor, or a moral offender. The enemy is an existential threat to the political community\u0026rsquo;s way of life — a group whose existence negates the community\u0026rsquo;s own form of existence so intensely that conflict becomes a real possibility.\n",
  "name": "Friend/Enemy Distinction",
